00:01:02.590 --> 00:01:05.796
But now I have to give a
serious answer to that serious

00:01:05.796 --> 00:01:08.186
question,
which I sort of mentioned

00:01:08.186 --> 00:01:12.144
before, which is that everything
I've done so far is for one

00:01:12.144 --> 00:01:13.420
instant in time.
 

00:01:13.420 --> 00:01:15.340
I hope I made it very clear.
 

00:01:15.340 --> 00:01:17.000
So here's the analogy.
 

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:19.232
If someone comes to you and
says, "Tell me all about

00:01:19.232 --> 00:01:20.110
Newtonian mechanics.
 

00:01:20.110 --> 00:01:20.840
How does it work?
 

00:01:20.840 --> 00:01:22.360
What's the scheme like?"
 

00:01:22.360 --> 00:01:26.849
You say, "At any instant
someone has to give you the x

00:01:26.849 --> 00:01:31.494
and p of that particle at that
time," and that's all you

00:01:31.494 --> 00:01:32.810
need to know.
 

00:01:32.810 --> 00:01:34.849
That's all you can ask and
that's all you need to know.

00:01:34.849 --> 00:01:38.699
Everything about that one
particle is completely given by

00:01:38.699 --> 00:01:39.730
this x and p.
 

00:01:39.730 --> 00:01:43.060
That is called a state.
 

00:01:43.060 --> 00:01:45.789
That's the complete description
of any system is called at

00:01:45.789 --> 00:01:47.992
state,
and a state in classical

00:01:47.992 --> 00:01:52.427
mechanics for one particle in
one dimension is just a pair of

00:01:52.427 --> 00:01:53.239
numbers.
 

00:01:53.239 --> 00:01:57.614
It's a state because given that
I can predict the future for

00:01:57.614 --> 00:01:58.060
you.
 

00:01:58.060 --> 00:02:01.596
I can predict the future
because if I knew the initial

00:02:01.596 --> 00:02:04.000
momentum, namely initial
velocity.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:07.292
I know how fast the guy is
moving, and I know where it is

00:02:07.292 --> 00:02:08.408
at the initial x.
 

00:02:08.408 --> 00:02:12.370
A tiny amount of time later
it'll be at x vt,

00:02:12.370 --> 00:02:14.348
but t is very small.
 

00:02:14.348 --> 00:02:18.449
Then since I know the
acceleration from Newton's Laws,

00:02:18.449 --> 00:02:20.438
which is rate of change of
velocity,

00:02:20.438 --> 00:02:24.311
if I knew the initial velocity
or initial momentum I can get

00:02:24.311 --> 00:02:26.280
the momentum a little later.
 

00:02:26.280 --> 00:02:28.840
Then in that manner I can inch
forward in time.

00:02:28.840 --> 00:02:32.902
So you need Newton's Laws,
and Newton's Laws tell you,

00:02:32.902 --> 00:02:36.045
if you like,
rate of change of momentum is

00:02:36.045 --> 00:02:37.120
the force.
 

00:02:37.120 --> 00:02:43.241
So if you like you can write
this mdx/dt squared is the

00:02:43.241 --> 00:02:44.150
force.
 

00:02:44.150 --> 00:02:48.807
So this part is called dynamics
and this part is called

00:02:48.807 --> 00:02:49.930
kinematics.
 

00:02:49.930 --> 00:02:52.330
So dynamics is how do things
change with time?

00:02:52.330 --> 00:02:56.348
Kinematics is what do you need
to know about the particle?

00:02:56.348 --> 00:02:59.729
In the quantum version of this
if you say,

00:02:59.729 --> 00:03:03.712
"What constitutes complete
knowledge of the

00:03:03.712 --> 00:03:07.358
particle?,"
the answer is this function

00:03:07.358 --> 00:03:08.460
ψ(x).
 

00:03:08.460 --> 00:03:11.675
If you knew this function you
know all that there is to know

00:03:11.675 --> 00:03:12.819
about the particle.
 

00:03:12.819 --> 00:03:14.479
We're not saying it's real.
 

00:03:14.479 --> 00:03:18.330
It can be complex.
 

00:03:18.330 --> 00:03:21.052
Then you can ask,
"If you knew the ψ

00:03:21.052 --> 00:03:24.210
at one time what's it going to
be later on?"

00:03:24.210 --> 00:03:26.169
That's the analog of this one.
 

00:03:26.169 --> 00:03:27.990
